      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm working on some embedded C++ code for an automotive ECU and i'm seeing a slow memory leak. The heap usage just keeps climbing over a few hours of driving simulation until it hits the limit and the system resets.\n\nHere is part of the allocation loop:\n\nvoid process_sensor_data(SensorPacket* packet) {\n    if (packet != nullptr) {\n        DataBuffer* buffer = new DataBuffer(packet->size);\n        buffer->copy_from(packet->payload);\n        log_buffer(buffer); \n        // ... processing logic ...\n    }\n}\n\nThe log_buffer function pushes the pointer to a global queue. I've checked the queue size and it seems to stay stable, but the RAM is definitely disappearing. How should i go about systematically finding where the leak is actually happening?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
